{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519130"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:09:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:09:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12976"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12976"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.9,0.03,0.01,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110691"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5414"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12976"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92939"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"183"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9142"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10560"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41719"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110691"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with a two-week history of worsening fatigue, generalised weakness, nausea, and dizziness on standing. She reports a 5 kg unintentional weight loss over the past three months. She was recently diagnosed with a self-limiting episode of infective gastroenteritis. Her medical history includes hypothyroidism due to autoimmune thyroiditis, for which she takes levothyroxine each morning. She does not take any other regular medications. She does not smoke or use alcohol, and works as a primary school teacher.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears tired. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure is 90/62 mmHg, respiratory rate is 18/min, SpO2 is 98% on room air, and temperature is 37.0\u00b0C. There is increased pigmentation in her buccal mucosa, palmar creases, and axillae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer laboratory results are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium: 128 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium: 5.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERandom blood glucose: 3.9 mmol/L (4.0-7.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThyroid stimulating hormone: 0.5 mIU/L (0.4-4)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMorning cortisol: 50 nmol/L (138-690)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdrenocorticotropic hormone: 90 pg/mL (10-60)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary adrenal insufficiency","Over-replacement of levothyroxine","Crohn\u0027s disease","Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion","Postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary adrenal insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E (Addison\u0027s disease) is characterised by deficient production of both glucocorticoids and mineralocorticoids due to destruction of the adrenal cortex, most commonly from autoimmune causes. This leads to low cortisol, high adrenocorticotropic hormone, hyponatraemia, hyperkalaemia, hypotension, and hyperpigmentation due to increased adrenocorticotropic hormone stimulating melanocyte-stimulating hormone receptors. The presence of another autoimmune condition (autoimmune thyroiditis) increases the likelihood of this diagnosis. The laboratory findings of low morning cortisol (50 nmol/L), elevated adrenocorticotropic hormone, hyponatraemia, and hyperkalaemia are classic for primary adrenal insufficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOver-replacement of levothyroxine\u003C/strong\u003E may cause symptoms such as weight loss, anxiety, tremor, and tachycardia, but would not explain the electrolyte abnormalities, hypotension, hyperpigmentation, or the hormonal findings of low cortisol and high adrenocorticotropic hormone. The thyroid stimulating hormone is within the reference interval, making this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E can present with weight loss and fatigue, but would typically be associated with gastrointestinal symptoms such as abdominal pain, diarrhoea, or blood in the stool. It does not explain the electrolyte disturbances, hyperpigmentation, or the hormonal findings seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESyndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion\u003C/strong\u003E can cause hyponatraemia and sometimes fatigue, but would not account for the hyperkalaemia, hypotension, hyperpigmentation, or the hormonal findings of low cortisol and high adrenocorticotropic hormone. There is also no history of malignancy, pulmonary, or central nervous system disease to suggest this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPostural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by orthostatic intolerance and tachycardia on standing, but does not cause electrolyte disturbances, hyperpigmentation, or abnormal cortisol and adrenocorticotropic hormone levels. The clinical and biochemical features in this case are not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary adrenal insufficiency presents with low cortisol, high adrenocorticotropic hormone, hyponatraemia, hyperkalaemia, and hyperpigmentation.","Autoimmune conditions such as Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis increase the risk of developing Addison\u0027s disease.","Careful interpretation of clinical and biochemical findings is essential to distinguish Addison\u0027s disease from other causes of fatigue and hypotension."],"references":["Barthel A, Benker G, Berens K, Diederich S, Manfras B, Gruber M, Kanczkowski W, Kline G, Kamvissi-Lorenz V, Hahner S, Beuschlein F, Brennand A, Boehm BO, Torpy DJ, Bornstein SR. An Update on Addison\u0027s Disease. Exp Clin Endocrinol Diabetes. 2019 Feb;127(2-03):165-175.","Betterle C, Presotto F, Furmaniak J. Epidemiology, pathogenesis, and diagnosis of Addison\u0027s disease in adults. J Endocrinol Invest. 2019 Dec;42(12):1407-1433."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92939"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12976"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92939"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-03T11:26:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-03T11:26:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5414"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110691"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":